You are working in a git repo that deploys by pushing to GitHub:
Repo: https://github.com/MatthewKehoeErgo/SBCI-Cursor-Prototype-v01
Default branch: main

RULE: When the user asks to "deploy", "publish", "push", or "sync" changes to GitHub:

1) Verify repo state first
- Run: git status -sb
- Confirm we're on the intended branch (usually main) and see what changed.

2) Never commit secrets or local-only files
- Do NOT add: .env, *.key, *.pem, credentials files, local config, or large build artifacts.
- Ensure node_modules/ and dist/ are not committed (use .gitignore).

3) Keep commits small and readable
- Stage intentionally: git add -A (or add specific paths if the change is targeted)
- Commit message format:
  - One short line describing intent, e.g. "Update dashboard layout"

4) Push safely
- If the change is small and the user explicitly wants it on main:
  - git push origin main
- Otherwise:
  - Create a feature branch: feature/<short-name>
  - Push: git push -u origin HEAD
  - Open a PR to main and include a short summary + test plan.

5) Post-push verification
- Re-run: git status -sb to confirm clean working tree and upstream tracking.

